<td>2.1×</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Named source only</td>
<td>1.6×</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Generic claim (no source)</td>
<td>Baseline</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>This effect is strongest for statistical and commercial intent queries. For definitional queries, attribution matters less because consensus facts do not require sourcing.</p>
<p><strong>Context:</strong> Named-source citations signal credibility to both human readers and AI extraction systems. When Google synthesizes an AI Overview, it prefers claims that are already attributed to recognized authorities. This reduces the risk of presenting unverified information.</p>
<p>The practical implication is clear: every statistic, every data point, and every factual claim in your content should carry a named source. Not a footnote at the bottom. An inline citation within the sentence that presents the claim.</p>
